  "objections": [
    {
      "severity": "high",
      "location": "src/frontend/web/src/App.tsx",
      "description": "React.lazy routes are wrapped in Suspense but lack an Error Boundary. If the isolated pdf-export chunk or any route chunk fails to load due to network interruption, cache corruption, or deployment rollback, the entire application crashes with an uncaught runtime error rather than gracefully degrading.",
      "suggested_fix": "Wrap the Suspense component with an ErrorBoundary that catches chunk load failures and renders a retry UI or fallback shell. Implement error logging to monitoring service for chunk load failures."
    },
    {
      "severity": "high",
      "location": "src/frontend/web/src/components/DocumentGraph.tsx",
      "description": "Backend-driven relation labels and document metadata are rendered without sanitization, creating an XSS attack vector. The manual chunk for sanitize exists in the bundle configuration but is not integrated into the graph rendering pipeline, allowing malicious scripts in document titles or relation types to execute.",
      "suggested_fix": "Import the sanitize utility from the dedicated chunk and apply it to all user-generated strings (branch labels, relation types, document titles) before rendering. Avoid dangerouslySetInnerHTML unless absolutely necessary; use textContent with sanitization as defense-in-depth."
    },
    {
      "severity": "medium",
      "location": "src/frontend/web/src/App.tsx",
      "description": "Suspense boundary provides null or undefined fallback, causing layout shift and blank white screens while lazy chunks load over mobile networks. This violates mobile-first requirements by providing poor perceived performance on 3G/4G connections.",
      "suggested_fix": "Provide an explicit fallback prop to Suspense with a PageSkeleton component that matches the AppShell layout dimensions to prevent cumulative layout shift (CLS)."
    },
    {
      "severity": "medium",
      "location": "src/frontend/web/vite.config.ts",
      "description": "Chunk warning limit raised to 700kb masks potential bundle bloat. While html2pdf is intentionally large, the 700kb threshold accepts multiple oversized chunks without scrutiny, defeating the purpose of granular code-splitting and impacting mobile parse times.",
